{"title_page": "Gilad Atzmon", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gilad Atzmon<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}\n| image=Gilad Atzmon.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Atzmon in concert, February 2007\n| birth_name = Gilad Atzmon\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|9}}\n| birth_place = Tel Aviv, Israel\n| known_for = Music, political activism\n| education = [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]], [[University of Essex]]\n| occupation = Musician, novelist\n| website = {{url|gilad.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Gilad Atzmon''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}, {{IPA-he|\u0261i\u02c8lad at\u0361s\u02c8mon|}}; born 9 June 1963) is a British [[jazz]] saxophonist, novelist, political activist, and writer.\n\nAtzmon has written novels, articles for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'', ''Uruknet'', and the ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',  and polemical works on [[Jewish identity]]. His criticisms of [[Zionism]], Jewish identity, and Judaism, and views on [[Holocaust denial]] and [[Jewish history]], have led to allegations of antisemitism.\n\n==Early life==\nAtzmon was born in a [[secular Jew]]ish family in Tel Aviv, Israel, [[Ashkenazi]] on his father's side,<ref name=\"Beauty\" /> and grew up in Jerusalem.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/haunted-by-ghosts-1.319263 |title=Haunted by Ghosts |first=Yaron |last=Frid |date=15 October 2010 |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=12 January 2018 }}</ref> His great-grandmother was a victim of World War II, but he refuses to assign her death a special [[Holocaust]] status.<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA175  ''The Wandering Who,'']  p. 175 \"Historical narratives do not need the protection of the law and political lobbies. It took me years to grasp that my great-grandmother wasn\u2019t made into a \u2018soap\u2019 or a \u2018lampshade\u2019 as I was taught in Israel. She probably perished of exhaustion, typhus or maybe even by mass shooting. This was indeed bad and tragic, but not that different from the fate of many millions of Ukrainians, on learning the real meaning of communism\".</ref> His grandfather was, he states, a commander in the paramilitary [[Irgun]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate in Palestine]], who subscribed to the [[Iron Wall (essay)|doctrines]] of [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]], hated Germans, despised the British, was angry with Palestinians for living on land that God had given to Jews, and loathed Jewish leftists.<ref name = WanderingBook /> For Atzmon he was a 'veteran [[Zionist political violence|Zionist terrorist]]', and he himself grew up in what he describes as a 'happy childhood'<ref>. Silvia Cattori [http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-wandering-who/2011/9/27/silvia-cattori-interviews-gilad-atzmon.html 'Interview with Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon.com 27 September 2011</ref> imbued with a spirit of 'militant enthusiasm.'<ref name = WanderingBook />\n\nAtzmon first became interested in the British variety of [[jazz]] when he came across some recordings of it in a British record shop in Jerusalem in the 1970s, and found inspiration in the work of [[Ronnie Scott]] and [[Tubby Hayes]] and regarded London as \"the Mecca of Jazz.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3647173/How-jazz-got-hot-again.html|title=How jazz got hot again|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|date=13 October 2005|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> However, at 17, while readying himself for induction into the army, he happened to hear a radio broadcast of a recording of [[Charlie Parker]]'s ''[[Charlie Parker with Strings|With Strings]]'' and was swept off his feet. Atzmon has said of the album that he \"loved the way the music is both beautiful and subversive&nbsp;\u2013 the way he basks in the strings but also fights against them.\"<ref name=Lewis>John Lewis [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/06/gilad-atzmon-israel-jazz-interview#history-byline \"Manic beat preacher\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 March 2009</ref> He skipped school to visit Jerusalem's Piccadilly Records outlet, and bought up every [[Bebop]] recording they stocked. Two days later, he purchased a saxophone.<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nAtzmon was [[Conscription in Israel|conscripted]] into the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) in June 1981. He began his service as a combat medic and participated in the [[1982 Lebanon War]]. Aztmon was transferred to a position within the [[Israel Defense Forces Orchestra]] and spent most of his military service in the [[Israeli Air Force]] orchestra. He explains this as a reflection of the fact that '\u2019(p)laying scales at the speed of light seemed to me far more important than killing Arabs in the name of Jewish suffering.\u2019 Three weeks before the end of his military service, in the wake of the war, his troupe visited an IDF detention camp at [[Ansar, Lebanon]]. He later wrote that this was a 'life-changing' experience, coming into direct contact with the conditions of captured Palestinians, some locked in [[solitary confinement]] in what he took at first to be 1 metre square concrete boxes for guard dogs. During a guided tour, he states that, as he peered across the barbed wire at the POWs, he felt that \u2018the place was a concentration camp. The inmates were the 'Jews', and I was nothing but a \u2018Nazi\u2019.'<ref name = WanderingBook/> After he was demobilised, he travelled to Europe in December 1984, living as a [[Street performer|busker]].<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nIn the following years, he trained at the [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]] in Jerusalem.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|work=People|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> During the late 1980s and 1990s Atzmon was a popular [[session musician]] and producer, recording extensively and performing with Israeli artists such as: [[Yehuda Poliker]], [[Yardena Arazi]], Si Himan, [[Meir Banai]] and [[Ofra Haza]]. Additionally, he started the first incarnation of the \"Gilad Atzmon Quartet\" and a group named \"Spiel Acid Jazz Band\" with fellow Israeli Jazz musicians, and performed regularly at the [[Red Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref name=haaretz />\n\nIn 1994, disenchanted with the implications of the [[Oslo Accords]],{{cn|date=April 2020}} Atzmon immigrated to the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"RainLore bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rainloresworldofmusic.net/Artists/Artists_A-D/Atzmon_Gilad.html|title=Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|date=21 March 2003|publisher=Rainlore's World of Music}}</ref>{{deadlink|date=April 2020}} attending the [[University of Essex]]<ref>[http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm University of Essex news release dated 14 December 2007 notes Atzmon is a \"graduate\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422032736/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}, Essex.ac.uk; accessed 27 February 2016.</ref> and earning a master's degree in Philosophy, according to ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref name=CP22515>{{cite news|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/05/22/on-gilad-atzmons-the-definitive-israeli-lexicon/|title=On Gilad Atzmon's Definitive Israeli Lexicon/|last=Schulman|first=Eugene|date=22 May 2015|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=CounterPunch}}</ref> while landing a residency as musician at the Irish [[Black Lion, Kilburn|Black Lion pub]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]].<ref name = WanderingBook/> He has lived subsequently in the UK,<ref name=\"gilchrist222\">{{cite news|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/39I-thought-music-could-heal.3804991.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000|title='I thought music could heal the wounds of the past. I may have got that wrong'|last=Gilchrist|first=Jim|date=22 February 2008|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref> becoming a British citizen in 2002, according to ''CounterPunch''<ref name=\"St. Clair\"/> and renouncing his Israeli citizenship.<ref name=\"Urbain\">Karen Abi-Ezzi, 'Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon,' in Olivier Urbain (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA93&dq=Atzmon+renounced+Israeli+citizenship ''Music and Conflict Transformation: Harmonies and Dissonances in Geopolitics,''] [[I. B. Tauris]], 2015 pp.93\u2013103, p. 93</ref>\n\n==Music==\nWhile Atzmon's main instrument is the alto saxophone, he also plays soprano, tenor and baritone saxophones and clarinet, [[Sol (instrument)|sol]], [[zurna]] and flute.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\" /><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Richard|year=2005|title=Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich|url-access=registration|publisher=Penguin Books| location = London | isbn = 0-141-00646-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich/page/23 23]}}</ref> Atzmon's jazz style has been described as [[bebop]]/[[hard bop]], with forays into [[free jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]], and seemingly inspired by [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=\"RainLore bio\" /> Atzmon sometimes plays the alto and soprano sax simultaneously.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/>\n\nAtzmon's works have also explored the music of the Middle East, North Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|title=GILAD ATZMON&nbsp;\u2013 MUSICIAN, COMPOSER, PRODUCER, EDUCATOR, WRITER|accessdate=28 October 2008|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2007|publisher=Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221120611/http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|archivedate=21 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Atzmon told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he draws on [[Arabic music]] which he says cannot be notated like western music but must be internalised, which he calls \"reverting to the primacy of the ear\". Atzmon's musical method has been to play with notions of cultural identity, flirting with genres such as tango and [[klezmer]] as well as various Arabic, Balkan, Gypsy and [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] folk forms. Atzmon's recordings deliberately differ from his live shows. \"I don't think that anyone can sit in a house, at home, and listen to me play a full-on bebop solo. It's too intense. My albums need to be less manic.\"<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Collaborations and groups===\nAtzmon joined the veteran [[punk rock]] band [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] in 1998, and continued with the Blockheads after Dury's death.<ref>Stephen Robb, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6253257.stm \"The old Blockheads shows go on\"], [[BBC News]], 25 January 2007.</ref><ref>Sara Greek, [http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm Blockheads come to Hertford Corn Exchange] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206100511/http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm |date=6 December 2013 }}, [[Hertfordshire Mercury]], 28 October 2011.</ref> He has recorded and performed with [[Shane MacGowan]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Robert Wyatt]] and [[Paul McCartney]].<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/><ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\"/> He has recorded two albums with Robert Wyatt, who describes him as \"one of the few musical geniuses I've ever met\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has collaborated, recorded and performed with musicians from all around the world, including the Palestinian singer, [[Reem Kelani]], Tunisian singer and [[oud]] player [[Dhafer Youssef]], violinist Marcel Mamaliga, accordion player Romano Viazzani, bassist Yaron Stavi, violinist and trumpet-violin player, Dumitru Ovidiu Fratila, and Guillermo Rozenthuler on vocals.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> He played tenor saxophone and clarinet on one track, \"Anisina\", on the 2014 Pink Floyd album, ''[[The Endless River]]''. He has worked with leading bands as a musical producer.<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], [http://www.tourdates.co.uk/ London Tour Dates], 5 October 2007.</ref>\n\nAtzmon founded the Orient House Ensemble band in London in 2000 with [[Asaf Sirkis]] on drums, Frank Harrison on piano and Oli Hayhurst on bass. In 2003 Yaron Stavi replaced Hayhurst. In 2009 Eddie Hick replaced Sirkis.<ref name=Ensemble>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-orient-house-ensemble/ Orient House Ensemble description at Gilad Atzmon home page.]</ref><ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/14/asaf-sirkis-letting-go-review Asaf Sirkis Trio: Letting Go \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 14 October 2010.</ref>  The group was named after [[Orient House]], the former [[East Jerusalem]] headquarters of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], later seized by the [[Israeli Defense Forces]].<ref>Jack Massarik, \"Gilad Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble\", [[Evening Standard]], 16 January 2006.</ref> The band has recorded eight albums. Orient House announced a 40-date tour in 2010.<ref name=Fordham>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/05/gilad-atzmon-orient-house-ensemble-review Gilad Atzmon Orient House Ensemble \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Wyatt]], who has said that Atzmon combines \"great artistry with a sense of the intrinsically non-racialist philosophy that's implicit in jazz,\"<ref>Lester Paul [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/26/best-band-rock-pop \"So who is top of the pops\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 June 2010.</ref> worked with Atzmon and others on his album ''[[Comicopera]]'' (2007).<ref>Chris Jones, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gwcz A national treasure makes another peerless album], [[BBC]], 5 October 2007.</ref> Wyatt collaborated with Atzmon and Ros Stephens, as well as lyricist [[Alfreda Benge]], on the album ''For the Ghosts Within'' (2010), released on [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]].<ref>Andy Gill, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-wyatt--atzmon--stephen-for-the-ghosts-within-domino-2102994.html Album: Wyatt, Atzmon, Stephen, For The Ghosts Within (Domino)], [[The Independent]], 8 October 2011.</ref><ref>Alex Hudson, [https://exclaim.ca/music/article/robert_wyatt_unveils_new_collaborative_album \"Robert Wyatt Unveils New Collaborative Album\"], [[Exclaim!]], 8 July 2010</ref>\n\nAtzmon produced and arranged two albums for [[Sarah Gillespie]] ''Stalking Juliet ''(2009) and ''In The Current Climate ''(2011). Both albums were critically acclaimed.<ref name=\"Guardian\">John Fordham [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/10/sarah-gillespie-stalking-juliet-review \"Stalking Juliet review\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 April 2009</ref> He has toured extensively as a member of Sarah Gillespie's band, playing saxophone, clarinet and accordion.<ref name=\"Metro\">[http://www.metro.co.uk/music/852007-jazz-your-cd-collection-up \"Robert Shaw, Guitarist Keeps Her Finger on the Pulse\"], Metro.co.uk, 6 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon is on the creative panel of the [[Global Music Foundation]],<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/> a non-profit organization formed in December 2004 which runs residential educational and performance workshops and events in different countries around the world.<ref name=\"GMF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad mAtzmon|accessdate=23 October 2017|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> and also offers personal workshops to students.<ref name=\"Atzmon-Workshop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/education-1/|title=MUSIC EDUCATION|accessdate=3 January 2018|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2015|publisher=Gilad Atzmon}}</ref> A musical transcription of ten saxophone solos by Atzmon was released in 2010.<ref>Chris Gumbley, [http://www.gumblespublications.co.uk/saxophone-solos/ Gilad Uncovered: 10 Transcriptions], Gumbles Publications, 2010.</ref>\n\nAccording to reviewer [[Chris Searle]] in 2010, writing in the ''[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', \"No jazz musicians have done more to honour, publicise and spread solidarity with the struggle of the Palestinians than Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble.\u201d<ref>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 Review of the book ''Jazz Jews'' by Mike Gerber] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175013/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 |date=23 October 2017 }}, ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', February 2010.</ref>\n\n===Reviews and awards===\nAtzmon and his ensemble have received favorable reviews from the ''[[Financial Times]]'', ''[[The Scotsman]]'', ''[[Birmingham Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Bacon|first=Peter|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CULTURE%3A+Arts+reviews%3A+Activist+with+quotes+and+plenty+to+say%3B+Gilad...-a0127526728|title=Activist with quotes and plenty to say; Gilad Atzmon CBSO Centre|work=Birmingham Post| date=24 January 2005|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon web site].</ref> Reviews of his 2007 album ''Refuge'' included:\n:''[[Manchester Evening News]]'': \"The individuality of the music is extraordinary. No one is more willing to serve his music with raw political passion, and that curious [[Hazzan|cantor]]-like tone on clarinet is immediately arresting, like [[Artie Shaw]] writhing in his death throes.\"<ref>Alan Brownlee, [http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/world_music/s/1015/1015003_gilad_atzmon__the_orient_house_ensemble__refuge_enja.html Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble&nbsp;\u2013 Refuge (Enja)], [[Manchester Evening News]], 30 August 2007.</ref>\n:[[BBC]]: \"...the OHE is finding its voice in an increasingly subtle blend of East and West, that\u2019s brutal and beautiful.\"<ref>Kathryn Shackleton, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/5vp2/ Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble, Refuge], [[BBC]], 1 October 2007.</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, ''[[The Guardian]]'' jazz critic [[John Fordham (jazz critic)|John Fordham]] reviewed Atzmon's newest album ''In loving memory of America'' which was described by Atzmon as \"a memory of America I had cherished in my mind for many years\". It includes five standards and six originals \"inspired by the sumptuous harmonies and impassioned sax-playing of [[Charlie Parker|(Charlie) Parker]]'s late-40s recordings with classical strings\".<ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/27/gilad-atzmon-loving-memory-america \"Gilad Atzmon: In Loving Memory of America\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 February 2009.</ref> Music journalist John Lewis has praised much of Atzmon's work and described Atzmon as \"one of London's finest saxophonists\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon was the recipient of the [[HMV]] ''Top Dog Award'' at the [[Jazz of Birmingham|Birmingham International Jazz Festival]] in 1996\u201398.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> Gilad Atzmon's ''Exile'' was BBC jazz album of the year in 2003.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/3107607.stm Jazz winners span generations], BBC, 30 July 2003.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nAtzmon has defined himself variously as a \"[[secular Jew]]\",<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> a \"proud self-hating Jew\"  in the style of [[Otto Weininger]],<ref name=\"Panayides\" >Theo Panayides, [https://web.archive.org/web/20100223072804/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/living/wandering-jazz-player/20100221 'Wandering jazz player,'], [[Cyprus Mail]], 21 February 2010: \"My ethical duty is to say the things that I know and feel. I\u2019m an artist. Do you know.. this is something I learned from Otto Weininger, the Austrian philosopher. He was a clever boy, killed himself when he was 21. ..He was definitely a proud self-hating Jew! I\u2019m not a self-hating Jew: I\u2019m a proud self-hating Jew! It\u2019s a big difference\u2026 I celebrate my hatred towards everything I represent \u2013 or better to say [everything] I\u2019m associated with\".</ref> an \"ex-Jew\",<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/a-new-jewish-goal-by-gilad-atzmon.html A New Jewish Goal], at his personal web site.</ref> \"a Jew who hates Judaism\",<ref>{{cite news|last=\u05d7\u05dc\u05d9\u05dc\u05d9|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d8\u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df|url=http://article.yedioth.co.il/default.aspx?articleid=5448|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=9 November 2011|language=Hebrew|quote=\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05e9\u05dd \u05d0\u05ea \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9 \u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d6\u05db\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05ea \u05de\u05d2\u05d3\u05dc\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d7\u05df \u05db\u05dc \u05d0\u05e1\u05e4\u05e7\u05d8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05db\u05d9. (As a Jew who hates Judaism, I put myself under a magnifying glass and examine every Jewish aspect in me).}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halily|first=Yaniv|title=The protocols of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4147243,00.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=14 November 2011}}</ref> and \"a Hebrew-speaking Palestinian\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/>\n\nHe has said: \"I don't write about politics, I write about ethics. I write about Identity. I write a lot about the [[Jewish Question]]&nbsp;\u2013 because I was born in the Jew-land, and my whole process in maturing into an adult was involved with the realisation that my people are living on stolen land.\"<ref name=\"Panayides\"/> Atzmon has said that his experience in the military of \"my people destroying other people left a big scar\" and led to his decision that he was deluded about Zionism.  Atzmon has compared \"the Jewish Ideology\" to that of the [[Nazis]] and has described Israel's policy toward the Palestinians as [[genocide]].<ref name=\"gibson\"/> He has condemned \"Jewishness\" as \"very much a supremacist, racist tendency\", but has also stated that \"I don't have anything against Jews in particular and you won't find that in my writings\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> Regarding the one-state solution, Atzmon concedes that such a state probably would be controlled by [[Islamist]]s, but says, \"That's their business\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has said his statements have lost him performance contracts, especially in the United States.<ref>Karen Abi-Ezzi, \"Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon\u201d, Chapter 7 of Olivier Urbain, Editor, ''Music and conflict transformation: harmonies and dissonances in geopolitics'', I.B. Tauris, 2008  [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA101&dq=urbain+atzmon+contracts&hl=en&ei=2wpFTPf2C8P88Ab03uDKDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 101].</ref> \n\n===Periodicals===\nAtzmon has written for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref>Examples of Gilad Atzmon in [[CounterPunch]]:[https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/09/18/vengeance-barbarism-and-tarantino-s-inglourious-basterds/ Vengeance, Barbarism and Tarantino's Inglourious Basterds], 18 September 2009; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/08/28/the-most-common-mistakes-of-israelis/ Collective Self-Deception: The Most Common Mistakes of Israelis], 28 August 2003; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/10/thinking-outside-of-the-secular-box/ The Left and Islam: Thinking Outside of the Secular Box], 10\u201312 July 2009.</ref> ''Uruknet'',<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://uruknet.info/?p=m31096&s1=h1 Purim Special, From Esther to AIPAC], Uruknet, 3 March 2007.</ref> and the ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',<ref>Example of Gilad Atzmon in ''The Palestine Telegraph'': [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/jewish-ideology-and-world-peace-by-gilad-atzmon.html 'Israeli Ideology and World Peace,'] 7 June 2010.</ref>. In 2009, he wrote for and edited the website, Palestine Think Tank.<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Novels===\nAtzmon's ''[[A Guide to the Perplexed]]'', published in 2001, is set in a 2052 in which Israel has been replaced by a Palestinian state. Jeffrey St. Clair in ''CounterPunch'' describes it as \"vividly written satire, infused with a ribald sense of humor and an unsparing critique of the incendiary political cauldron of the Mideast.\" It largely reviews memoirs of the alienated Israeli Gunther Wunker's rise to fame as a \"peepologist\", or voyeur. The perplexed are defined as \"the unthinking Chosen\" who \"cling to clods of earth that don't belong to them.\" The novel excoriates what it describes as the commercialization of the Holocaust and \"argues that the Holocaust is invoked as a kind of reflexive propaganda designed to shield the Zionist state from responsibility for any transgression against Palestinians.\"<ref name=\"St. Clair\">[[Jeffrey St. Clair]],[https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/07/17/gilad-atzmon-s-a-guide-to-the-perplexed/ 'Gilad Atzmon's \"A Guide to the Perplexed\",'] [[CounterPunch]] 17 July 2003</ref>\n\nMatthew J. Reisz, a reviewer for ''[[The Independent]]'', wrote that \"As a viciously black satire on Israeli life\" the book \"is grandiose, childish and nasty, but with just enough connection with reality to give it a certain unsettling power\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Reisz|first=Matthew J.|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/a-guide-to-the-perplexed-by-gilad-atzmon-trans-philip-simpson-609999.html|title=A Guide to the Perplexed, by Gilad Atzmon, trans. Philip Simpson|work=The Independent|date=7 December 2002|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} Darren King in ''[[The Observer]]'' noted of this \"provocative debut novel\" that it is \"odd to mix knob gags with highly serious assertions\", but thought it works because \"Atzmon writes with so much style and his gags are so hilarious\".<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Darren|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/featuresreviews.guardianreview16|title=Mr. Peepology|work=The Observer|date=25 January 2003|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', \"Atzmon clearly wants to provoke, but his approach is so familiar that few readers will take the bait.\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-85242-826-6 \"A Guide to the Perplexed\"], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', 31 March 2003.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's second novel, ''My One and Only Love'', was published in 2005 and features as a protagonist a trumpeter who chooses to play only one note (extremely well), as well as a spy who uncovers Nazi war criminals and locks them inside double bass cases which then tour permanently in the protagonist's orchestra's luggage.<ref>Sholto Byrnes. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/talking-jazz-529796.html \"Talking Jazz\"], ''The Independent'', 25 March 2005</ref> The book is also a comedic take on \"Zionist espionage and intrigue\" which explores \"the personal conflict between being true to one\u2019s heart and being loyal to The Jews\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2004/10/01/gilad_event_feature.shtml \"Gilad Atzmon's Orient House Ensemble \u2013 The Junction\"], BBC Cambridgeshire, 3 June 2005.</ref>\n\n===Nonfiction===\nIn 2011, [[Zero Books]] published Atzmon's book, ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics'', stating that it \"examines Jewish identity politics and Jewish contemporary ideology using both popular culture and scholarly texts.\"<ref name = WanderingBook>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=rTbtBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&lpg=PT7 ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics''], Zero Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84694-875-6}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jean Bricmont]], in his preface for the French edition, ''La Parabole d\u2019Esther'', Atzmon starts by giving three definitions of 'Jewish': (a) it may refer to adherents of Judaism, and he has no quarrel with them; (b) secondly, it may refer to ethnic Jews, and, likewise, he sees no problem in that; (c) thirdly, it can refer to a third category, those who, without being particularly religious, place great emphasis on their Jewish \"identity\" as something more important than their basic membership of the human race.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" >[[Jean Bricmont]], [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/counterpunch-print-edition-in-defense-of-gilad-atzmon-by-jea.html  'In Defense of Gilad Atzmon By Jean Bricmont,'] Counterpunch April 2012 print edition, cited on Atzmon's blog.</ref> Bricmont then adds that it is very easy to mount a case to 'prove' Atzmon is an antisemite by consistently construing his criticisms of (c) as though they were aimed as (a) or (b) or both.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" /> \n\n[[Marc H. Ellis]],  professor of Jewish studies at [[Baylor University]], likens Atzmon's rhetorical extremism and harsh censure of Jews to the [[Prophet|prophetic voices]] of the [[Old Testament]], arguing that, for Atzmon, [[Diaspora|diasporic]] Jews are asked to construct their identity on the basis of the [[State of Israel]] and the [[Holocaust]], an identity he regards as without foundation. He adds that Atzmon considers charges that he is antisemitic as 'last ditch attempts' to validate that identity. In Ellis's view, there may be, in the perceived anxiety in these repeated attacks, a reflection of the same anxiety Atzmon himself arguably embodies.<ref name=\"Ellis\" >[[Marc H. Ellis]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=doN-AwAAQBAJ&dq=Marc+Ellis%2BGilad+Atzmon&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y  ''Future of the Prophetic: Israel's Ancient Wisdom Re-presented,''] [[Fortress Press]], 2014 pp.331\u2013332.</ref><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/the-new-jewish-prophet.html  'The New Jewish Prophet,'] 24 June 2014.</ref> {{efn|Ellis also notes that Atzmon considers the bible 'bogus'.<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> Atzmon himself cites evidence 600 passages in the OT are violent, and argues that this 'lethal spirit of the scriptures has infused the essence of modern Jewish political discourse,' underwriting in his view even the secular mindset of military commanders conducting war in Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.<ref>G. Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA122 ''The Wandering Who,''] 2011 p.122.</ref>}}\n\nRichard Falk commented \"Atzmon has written an absorbing and moving account of his journey from hard-core Israeli nationalist to a de-Zionized patriot of humanity\".<ref>Stephen M. Walt,[http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], 26 September 2011 (posted on Walt.Foreignpolicy.com)</ref> \n\nMearsheimer wrote \"There is no question that the book is provocative, both in terms of its central argument and the overly hot language that Atzmon sometimes uses. But it is also filled with interesting insights that make the reader think long and hard about an important subject.\"\nadding, \"to be perfectly clear, he has no animus toward Judaism as a religion or with individuals who are Jewish by birth. Rather, his target is the tribalism that he believes is common to most Jews, and I might add, to most other peoples as well.\"<ref>Stephen Walt, [http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref> \n\nTen authors published by Zero Books, including [[Laurie Penny]] and [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]], criticised Zero Books for publishing it, arguing that \"The thrust of Atzmon's work is to normalise and legitimise anti-Semitism.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leninology.blogspot.com/2011/09/zero-authors-statement-on-gilad-atzmon.html|title=Zero Authors Statement on Gilad Atzmon|publisher=Lenin's Tomb|date=26 September 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAtzmon characterised some of the criticism as an \"orchestrated attack\" and a \"typical [[Hasbara]] smear & intimidation campaign\u201d<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/goldberg-vs-mearsheimer-by-gilad-atzmon.html Goldberg vs. Mearsheimer], Gilad Atzmon website, 25 September 2011.</ref> and wrote that his book \"is a study of Jewish identity politics and Jewish culture, it is not concerned with Jewish ethnicity or racial origins.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-supremacists-on-the-wandering-who.html \"Supremacists on 'The Wandering Who'\"], Gilad.co.uk, 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's 2015 book, ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon'', was summarised by Eugene Schulman in ''CounterPunch'' as \"designed to alphabetically define certain aspects of Zionism and Zionist personalities in one-liner jabs.\" and called it as a book which would \"knock a hole in all your prejudices.\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/05/22/on-gilad-atzmons-the-definitive-israeli-lexicon/|title=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/05/22/on-gilad-atzmons-the-definitive-israeli-lexicon/|last=Schulman|first=Eugene|date=22 May 2015|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=CounterPunch}}</ref>\n\nAtzmon's fifth book, ''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', published in 2017, was described by [[James Petras]] as \"a brilliant and substantive critique of identity politics and Jewish political ideology and culture\" and as \"an essential read for understanding and confronting authoritarianism of all stripes and colors.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gilad.online/being-in-time|title=Endorsements|last=Petras|first=James|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=Gilad}}</ref> [[Keith Kahn-Harris]], in an opinion piece, argued that its critique of identity politics and ascription of it to Jewishness was inherently antisemitic.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kahn-Harris|first=Keith|url=https://forward.com/opinion/389696/cloaked-in-pretensions-gilad-atzmons-anti-semitism-soldiers-on/|title=Cloaked In Pretensions, Gilad Atzmon\u2019s Anti-Semitism Soldiers On|work=Forward|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of antisemitism==\nSeveral of Atzmon's statements regarding Jews and Judaism have led to allegations of antisemitism. \n\n===Criticism===\nIn a 2005 opinion piece, [[David Aaronovitch]] criticized Atzmon for his essay \"On Anti-Semitism\" and for making the case for free speech on the Holocaust.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\">{{cite news|last=Aaronovitch|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-did-the-far-left-manage-to-slip-into-bed-with-the-jew-hating-right-766cbwpdqfd|title=How did the far Left manage to slip into bed with the Jew-hating Right?|work=The Times|location=London|date=28 June 2005|accessdate=24 February 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 opinion piece, [[David Hirsh]] criticised what he called Atzmon's \"openly anti-Jewish rhetoric\", including [[Jewish deicide]].<ref>Hirsh, David. [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/nov/30/anewmenacingcurrentisappe Openly embracing prejudice], ''The Guardian'', 30 November 2006. Hirsh also refers to the statement in [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/apr/03/nobodyhaseverclaimedthatc \"What charge?\"], \"The Guardian\", 3 April 2006.</ref> In response to a question about this Atzmon replied, in ''CounterPunch'', \"I find it astonishing that people today happen to be offended by such accusations (i.e. about an event almost 2000 years ago.)\"<ref>[https://www.counterpunch.org/2007/02/15/quot-do-i-look-like-the-pope-quot/ \"Are You a Christian?\" \"Do I Look Like the Pope?\"&nbsp;\u2013 An Exchange Between Lenni Brenner & Gilad Atzmon], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 15 February 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, David Landy, an Irish academic and former chair of the Ireland Palestine Solidarity Campaign, wrote that Atzmon's words, \"if not actually anti-Semitic, certainly border on it\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Landy|first=David|title=Jewish Identity and Palestinian Rights: Disapora Jewish Opposition to Israel|year=2011|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-84813-926-8|page=167}}</ref> \n\nA group of mainly US-based Palestinian activists, including [[Ali Abunimah]], [[Naseer Aruri]], [[Omar Barghouti]], [[Nadia Hijab]] and [[Joseph Massad]], called in March 2012 for \"the disavowal of Atzmon by fellow Palestinian organizers, as well as Palestine solidarity activists, and allies of the Palestinian people\" and affirming that \"we regard any attempt to link and adopt antisemitic or racist language, even if it is within a self-described anti-imperialist and anti-Zionist politics, as reaffirming and legitimizing Zionism.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Granting No Quarter: A Call for the Disavowal of the Racism and Antisemitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://uspcn.org/2012/03/13/granting-no-quarter-a-call-for-the-disavowal-of-the-racism-and-antisemitism-of-gilad-atzmon|publisher=US Palestinian Community Network|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[Anti-Defamation League]] described Atzmon as \"an outspoken promoter of classic anti-Semitic conspiracy theories and a fierce\ncritic of the State of Israel (who) has engaged in Holocaust diminution and has defended the right of\nHolocaust deniers to challenge historical narratives and offer revisionist theories about the Holocaust.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/profiles/gilad-atzmon|title=Gilad Atzmon|publisher=ADL|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Comments===\nAt a talk by Richard Falk at [[London School of Economics|LSE]] in March 2017, which was being disrupted by pro-Israel activists, Atzmon was alleged to have commented that Jews had been \"expelled from Germany for misbehaving\" and also to have suggested that people should read Holocaust denier [[David Irving]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-students-told-dont-study-at-lse-by-board-president/|title=Jewish students told 'don\u2019t study at LSE' by Board president|work=Jewish News Online|date=23 March 2017|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Responses===\nAtzmon refers to charges of antisemitism as being a \"common Zionist silencing apparatus.\"<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], Interview with Gilad Atzmon in ''London Tour Dates'' magazine, 5 October 2006</ref> He denies that he is an antisemite and states that, \"Because 'Anti-Semite' is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have.\"<ref name=1001Lies>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/1001-lies-about-gilad-atzmon.html 1001 Lies About Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon com. 18 June 2011 \"I am an anti Zionist and oppose the Zionist mindset. I look at questions of Jewish identity and I do question the ties between a Jewish world view and Zionism. I refute totally that I am anti-Semite. In fact I also believe that the current concept of an Anti-Semitism is meaningless. Once the Zionists had managed to establish their Jewish state, any form of anti Jewish sentiments should be comprehended either as a private case of xenophobia or as a political retaliation to Israeli/Zionist atrocities. In other words, the title Anti-Semite became an \u2018empty signifier, i.e. a signifier with a vague, highly variable, unspecifiable or non-existent signified. It is an empty verbal utterance that exists merely to serve a political cause (very much like Blair\u2019s WMD and Bush\u2019s Axis of Evil). Because Anti-Semite is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have\".</ref> In 2009, Atzmon said \"I've got nothing against the Semite people, I don't have anything against people&nbsp;\u2014 I'm anti-Jewish, not anti-Jews.\"<ref name=\"gibson\">Gibson, Martin. \"No choice but to speak out&nbsp;\u2014 Israeli musician 'a proud self-hating Jew'\", ''The Gisborne Herald'', 23 January 2009.</ref> He added that \"Stupidly we interpreted the Nazi defeat as a vindication of the Jewish ideology and the Jewish people\"; however, \"in fact Jewish ideology and Nazi ideology were very similar.\"<ref name=\"gibson\"/> \n\nAtzmon has stated \" I do not deny the Holocaust or the Nazi Judeocide. But I just insist that both the Holocaust and World War II should be treated as historical events rather than as religious myth....The most crucial question here is why we are not allowed to treat that very historical chapter applying academic methods. The answer is very simple. The Holocaust is now regarded by most Jews and Anglo-Americans as the new Western religion...But then, even if we accept the Holocaust as the new Anglo-American liberal-democratic religion, we must allow people to be atheists.\"<ref name=\"Beauty\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|title=Beauty as a political weapon; Three in one: jazzman, writer and activist&nbsp;\u2013 A conversation with Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072556/http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|archivedate=3 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Talens\" >[[:es:Manuel Talens|Manuel Talens]],  [http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=24333 'La belleza como arma pol\u00edtica,'] [[Rebelion.org]] 19 December 2005,</ref> \n\n[[Oren Ben-Dor]] wrote in ''CounterPunch'' in 2008 \"I am firmly convinced that these vulgar attempts at silencing of Gilad and other courageous voices offends against supremely thoughtful, compassionate and egalitarian intellectual endeavours.\"<ref>[[Oren Ben-Dor]], [https://www.counterpunch.org/2008/03/15/the-silencing-of-gilad-atzmon/ 'The Silencing of Gilad Atzmon'], [[CounterPunch]], 15 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[Norton Mezvinsky]] wrote that \"Gilad Atzmon is a critical and committed secular humanist with firm views, who delights in being provocative.\"<ref>[[Norton Mezvinsky]], [http://wrmea.org/archives/507-washington-report-archives-2011-2015/may-2012/11161-gilad-atzmon-and-the-wandering-who.html Gilad Atzmon and The Wandering Who?], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.wrmea.org/action-alert-archives/11194-engaging-gilad-atzmon.html 'Engaging Gilad Atzmon], video of Norton Mezvinsky interview with Gilad Atzmon,' [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref>\n\n==Libel suit==\nIn July 2018, Atzmon issued an apology to Gideon Falter, the chairman of the [[Campaign Against Antisemitism]] after being sued for libel. Atzmon had alleged that Falter had personally profited from fabricating antisemitic incidents. Atzmon was also liable for legal costs and damages.<ref name=\"Libel\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Ben |title=Gilad Atzmon is forced to apologise to CAA's Gideon Falter over libel |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/gideon-falter-gilad-atzmon-1.466405 |accessdate=3 July 2018 |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CAA\">{{cite web |title=Antisemitic author and saxophonist Gilad Atzmon capitulates, making humiliating apology and paying substantial damages and costs after just two hours in court against CAA |url=https://antisemitism.uk/antisemitic-author-and-saxophonist-gilad-atzmon-capitulates-making-humiliating-apology-and-paying-substantial-damages-and-costs-after-just-two-hours-in-court-against-caa/ |website=antisemitism.uk |publisher=Campaign Against Antisemitism |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The Spirit of Trane'' (Fanfare Jazz, 2017)\n*''World Peace Trio'' (Enja, 2017)\n*''Songs of the Metropolis'' (World Village, 2013)\n*''The Tide Has Changed'' (World Village, 2010)\n*''In Loving Memory of America'' (Enja, 2009)\n*''Refuge'' (Enja, 2007)\n*''Artie Fishel and the Promised Band'' (WMD, 2006)\n*''MusiK'' (Enja, 2004)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/oct/08/jazz.shopping1</ref>\n*''Exile'' (Enja, 2004)\n*''Nostalgico'' (Enja, 2001)\n*''Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble'' (Enja, 2000)\n*''Juizz Muzic'' (FruitBeard, 1999)\n*''Take It or Leave It'' (Face Jazz, 1997)\n*''Spiel: Both Sides'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel Acid Jazz Band'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel'' (In Acoustic & H.M. Acoustica, 1993)\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book |title=[[A Guide to the Perplexed]] |translator= Philip Simpson |location=London|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]] |year=2002 |isbn=1-85242-826-0}}\n*''My one and only love''. London: Saqi Books, 2005. {{ISBN|0-86356-507-7}} (pbk.). {{ISBN|978-0-86356-507-6}} (pbk.)\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C| title=The Wandering Who?: A Study of Jewish Identity Politics |publisher=[[John Hunt Publishing|Zero Books]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-84694-875-6}}\n* ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon''. London, Fanfare Press, 2015.{{ISBN|978-0993183706}} (pbk.). \n*''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', Newbold on Stour, Warwickshire: Skyscraper Publications, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1911072201}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brian Lenzo, [http://www.palestinechronicle.com/old/view_article_details.php?id=16132 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed: Each Village is a Reminder], originally published by Socialist Worker Online, 13 July 2010 (reprinted by the Palestine Chronicle).{{Deadlink|date=April 2020}}\n*[http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/eveningnews24/norwich-whats-on-guide/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=GoingOutMusic&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=WhatsOn&itemid=NOED26%20Nov%202009%2016%3A03%3A06%3A953 Interview: Gilad Atzmon] by Rob Garratt, Evening News 24, 11 November 2009.{{Deadlink|date=April 2020}}\n*[https://archive.org/details/GiladAtzmonOnArabvoices.netJune2009 Gilad Atzmon interview on ArabVoices.net], [[KPFT]], June 2009 during visit to Houston, Texas.\n*Ivan Hewett, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3667959/Gilad-Altzmon-High-flown-ecstasies-from-an-angry-man.html Gilad Altzmon: High-flown ecstasies from an angry man], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 17 September 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133806/http://middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21321 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed by Mary Rizzo], Middle East Online, July 2007.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon website]\n\n{{The Blockheads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atzmon, Gilad}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:Anti-Judaism]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism]]\n[[Category:Bebop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:The Blockheads members]]\n[[Category:British jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:British male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Writers on Zionism]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gilad Atzmon<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}\n| image=Gilad Atzmon.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Atzmon in concert, February 2007\n| birth_name = Gilad Atzmon\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|9}}\n| birth_place = Tel Aviv, Israel\n| known_for = Music, political activism\n| education = [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]], [[University of Essex]]\n| occupation = Musician, novelist\n| website = {{url|gilad.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Gilad Atzmon''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}, {{IPA-he|\u0261i\u02c8lad at\u0361s\u02c8mon|}}; born 9 June 1963) is a British [[jazz]] saxophonist, novelist, political activist, and writer.\n\nAtzmon has written novels, articles for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'', ''Uruknet'', and the ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',  and polemical works on [[Jewish identity]]. His criticisms of [[Zionism]], Jewish identity, and Judaism, and views on [[Holocaust denial]] and [[Jewish history]], have led to allegations of antisemitism.\n\n==Early life==\nAtzmon was born in a [[secular Jew]]ish family in Tel Aviv, Israel, [[Ashkenazi]] on his father's side,<ref name=\"Beauty\" /> and grew up in Jerusalem.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/haunted-by-ghosts-1.319263 |title=Haunted by Ghosts |first=Yaron |last=Frid |date=15 October 2010 |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=12 January 2018 }}</ref> His great-grandmother was a victim of World War II, but he refuses to assign her death a special [[Holocaust]] status.<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA175  ''The Wandering Who,'']  p. 175 \"Historical narratives do not need the protection of the law and political lobbies. It took me years to grasp that my great-grandmother wasn\u2019t made into a \u2018soap\u2019 or a \u2018lampshade\u2019 as I was taught in Israel. She probably perished of exhaustion, typhus or maybe even by mass shooting. This was indeed bad and tragic, but not that different from the fate of many millions of Ukrainians, on learning the real meaning of communism\".</ref> His grandfather was, he states, a commander in the paramilitary [[Irgun]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate in Palestine]], who subscribed to the [[Iron Wall (essay)|doctrines]] of [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]], hated Germans, despised the British, was angry with Palestinians for living on land that God had given to Jews, and loathed Jewish leftists.<ref name = WanderingBook /> For Atzmon he was a 'veteran [[Zionist political violence|Zionist terrorist]]', and he himself grew up in what he describes as a 'happy childhood'<ref>. Silvia Cattori [http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-wandering-who/2011/9/27/silvia-cattori-interviews-gilad-atzmon.html 'Interview with Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon.com 27 September 2011</ref> imbued with a spirit of 'militant enthusiasm.'<ref name = WanderingBook />\n\nAtzmon first became interested in the British variety of [[jazz]] when he came across some recordings of it in a British record shop in Jerusalem in the 1970s, and found inspiration in the work of [[Ronnie Scott]] and [[Tubby Hayes]] and regarded London as \"the Mecca of Jazz.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3647173/How-jazz-got-hot-again.html|title=How jazz got hot again|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|date=13 October 2005|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> However, at 17, while readying himself for induction into the army, he happened to hear a radio broadcast of a recording of [[Charlie Parker]]'s ''[[Charlie Parker with Strings|With Strings]]'' and was swept off his feet. Atzmon has said of the album that he \"loved the way the music is both beautiful and subversive&nbsp;\u2013 the way he basks in the strings but also fights against them.\"<ref name=Lewis>John Lewis [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/06/gilad-atzmon-israel-jazz-interview#history-byline \"Manic beat preacher\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 March 2009</ref> He skipped school to visit Jerusalem's Piccadilly Records outlet, and bought up every [[Bebop]] recording they stocked. Two days later, he purchased a saxophone.<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nAtzmon was [[Conscription in Israel|conscripted]] into the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) in June 1981. He began his service as a combat medic and participated in the [[1982 Lebanon War]]. Aztmon was transferred to a position within the [[Israel Defense Forces Orchestra]] and spent most of his military service in the [[Israeli Air Force]] orchestra. He explains this as a reflection of the fact that '\u2019(p)laying scales at the speed of light seemed to me far more important than killing Arabs in the name of Jewish suffering.\u2019 Three weeks before the end of his military service, in the wake of the war, his troupe visited an IDF detention camp at [[Ansar, Lebanon]]. He later wrote that this was a 'life-changing' experience, coming into direct contact with the conditions of captured Palestinians, some locked in [[solitary confinement]] in what he took at first to be 1 metre square concrete boxes for guard dogs. During a guided tour, he states that, as he peered across the barbed wire at the POWs, he felt that \u2018the place was a concentration camp. The inmates were the 'Jews', and I was nothing but a \u2018Nazi\u2019.'<ref name = WanderingBook/> After he was demobilised, he travelled to Europe in December 1984, living as a [[Street performer|busker]].<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nIn the following years, he trained at the [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]] in Jerusalem.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|work=People|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> During the late 1980s and 1990s Atzmon was a popular [[session musician]] and producer, recording extensively and performing with Israeli artists such as: [[Yehuda Poliker]], [[Yardena Arazi]], Si Himan, [[Meir Banai]] and [[Ofra Haza]]. Additionally, he started the first incarnation of the \"Gilad Atzmon Quartet\" and a group named \"Spiel Acid Jazz Band\" with fellow Israeli Jazz musicians, and performed regularly at the [[Red Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref name=haaretz />\n\nIn 1994, disenchanted with the implications of the [[Oslo Accords]],{{cn|date=April 2020}} Atzmon immigrated to the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"RainLore bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rainloresworldofmusic.net/Artists/Artists_A-D/Atzmon_Gilad.html|title=Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|date=21 March 2003|publisher=Rainlore's World of Music}}</ref>{{deadlink|date=April 2020}} attending the [[University of Essex]]<ref>[http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm University of Essex news release dated 14 December 2007 notes Atzmon is a \"graduate\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422032736/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}, Essex.ac.uk; accessed 27 February 2016.</ref> and earning a master's degree in Philosophy, according to ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/05/22/on-gilad-atzmons-the-definitive-israeli-lexicon/|title=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/05/22/on-gilad-atzmons-the-definitive-israeli-lexicon/|last=Schulman|first=Eugene|date=22 May 2015|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=CounterPunch}}</ref> while landing a residency as musician at the Irish [[Black Lion, Kilburn|Black Lion pub]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]].<ref name = WanderingBook/> He has lived subsequently in the UK,<ref name=\"gilchrist222\">{{cite news|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/39I-thought-music-could-heal.3804991.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000|title='I thought music could heal the wounds of the past. I may have got that wrong'|last=Gilchrist|first=Jim|date=22 February 2008|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref> becoming a British citizen in 2002, according to ''CounterPunch''<ref name=\"St. Clair\"/> and renouncing his Israeli citizenship.<ref name=\"Urbain\">Karen Abi-Ezzi, 'Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon,' in Olivier Urbain (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA93&dq=Atzmon+renounced+Israeli+citizenship ''Music and Conflict Transformation: Harmonies and Dissonances in Geopolitics,''] [[I. B. Tauris]], 2015 pp.93\u2013103, p. 93</ref>\n\n==Music==\nWhile Atzmon's main instrument is the alto saxophone, he also plays soprano, tenor and baritone saxophones and clarinet, [[Sol (instrument)|sol]], [[zurna]] and flute.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\" /><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Richard|year=2005|title=Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich|url-access=registration|publisher=Penguin Books| location = London | isbn = 0-141-00646-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich/page/23 23]}}</ref> Atzmon's jazz style has been described as [[bebop]]/[[hard bop]], with forays into [[free jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]], and seemingly inspired by [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=\"RainLore bio\" /> Atzmon sometimes plays the alto and soprano sax simultaneously.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/>\n\nAtzmon's works have also explored the music of the Middle East, North Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|title=GILAD ATZMON&nbsp;\u2013 MUSICIAN, COMPOSER, PRODUCER, EDUCATOR, WRITER|accessdate=28 October 2008|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2007|publisher=Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221120611/http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|archivedate=21 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Atzmon told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he draws on [[Arabic music]] which he says cannot be notated like western music but must be internalised, which he calls \"reverting to the primacy of the ear\". Atzmon's musical method has been to play with notions of cultural identity, flirting with genres such as tango and [[klezmer]] as well as various Arabic, Balkan, Gypsy and [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] folk forms. Atzmon's recordings deliberately differ from his live shows. \"I don't think that anyone can sit in a house, at home, and listen to me play a full-on bebop solo. It's too intense. My albums need to be less manic.\"<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Collaborations and groups===\nAtzmon joined the veteran [[punk rock]] band [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] in 1998, and continued with the Blockheads after Dury's death.<ref>Stephen Robb, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6253257.stm \"The old Blockheads shows go on\"], [[BBC News]], 25 January 2007.</ref><ref>Sara Greek, [http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm Blockheads come to Hertford Corn Exchange] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206100511/http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm |date=6 December 2013 }}, [[Hertfordshire Mercury]], 28 October 2011.</ref> He has recorded and performed with [[Shane MacGowan]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Robert Wyatt]] and [[Paul McCartney]].<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/><ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\"/> He has recorded two albums with Robert Wyatt, who describes him as \"one of the few musical geniuses I've ever met\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has collaborated, recorded and performed with musicians from all around the world, including the Palestinian singer, [[Reem Kelani]], Tunisian singer and [[oud]] player [[Dhafer Youssef]], violinist Marcel Mamaliga, accordion player Romano Viazzani, bassist Yaron Stavi, violinist and trumpet-violin player, Dumitru Ovidiu Fratila, and Guillermo Rozenthuler on vocals.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> He played tenor saxophone and clarinet on one track, \"Anisina\", on the 2014 Pink Floyd album, ''[[The Endless River]]''. He has worked with leading bands as a musical producer.<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], [http://www.tourdates.co.uk/ London Tour Dates], 5 October 2007.</ref>\n\nAtzmon founded the Orient House Ensemble band in London in 2000 with [[Asaf Sirkis]] on drums, Frank Harrison on piano and Oli Hayhurst on bass. In 2003 Yaron Stavi replaced Hayhurst. In 2009 Eddie Hick replaced Sirkis.<ref name=Ensemble>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-orient-house-ensemble/ Orient House Ensemble description at Gilad Atzmon home page.]</ref><ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/14/asaf-sirkis-letting-go-review Asaf Sirkis Trio: Letting Go \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 14 October 2010.</ref>  The group was named after [[Orient House]], the former [[East Jerusalem]] headquarters of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], later seized by the [[Israeli Defense Forces]].<ref>Jack Massarik, \"Gilad Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble\", [[Evening Standard]], 16 January 2006.</ref> The band has recorded eight albums. Orient House announced a 40-date tour in 2010.<ref name=Fordham>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/05/gilad-atzmon-orient-house-ensemble-review Gilad Atzmon Orient House Ensemble \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Wyatt]], who has said that Atzmon combines \"great artistry with a sense of the intrinsically non-racialist philosophy that's implicit in jazz,\"<ref>Lester Paul [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/26/best-band-rock-pop \"So who is top of the pops\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 June 2010.</ref> worked with Atzmon and others on his album ''[[Comicopera]]'' (2007).<ref>Chris Jones, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gwcz A national treasure makes another peerless album], [[BBC]], 5 October 2007.</ref> Wyatt collaborated with Atzmon and Ros Stephens, as well as lyricist [[Alfreda Benge]], on the album ''For the Ghosts Within'' (2010), released on [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]].<ref>Andy Gill, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-wyatt--atzmon--stephen-for-the-ghosts-within-domino-2102994.html Album: Wyatt, Atzmon, Stephen, For The Ghosts Within (Domino)], [[The Independent]], 8 October 2011.</ref><ref>Alex Hudson, [https://exclaim.ca/music/article/robert_wyatt_unveils_new_collaborative_album \"Robert Wyatt Unveils New Collaborative Album\"], [[Exclaim!]], 8 July 2010</ref>\n\nAtzmon produced and arranged two albums for [[Sarah Gillespie]] ''Stalking Juliet ''(2009) and ''In The Current Climate ''(2011). Both albums were critically acclaimed.<ref name=\"Guardian\">John Fordham [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/10/sarah-gillespie-stalking-juliet-review \"Stalking Juliet review\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 April 2009</ref> He has toured extensively as a member of Sarah Gillespie's band, playing saxophone, clarinet and accordion.<ref name=\"Metro\">[http://www.metro.co.uk/music/852007-jazz-your-cd-collection-up \"Robert Shaw, Guitarist Keeps Her Finger on the Pulse\"], Metro.co.uk, 6 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon is on the creative panel of the [[Global Music Foundation]],<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/> a non-profit organization formed in December 2004 which runs residential educational and performance workshops and events in different countries around the world.<ref name=\"GMF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad mAtzmon|accessdate=23 October 2017|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> and also offers personal workshops to students.<ref name=\"Atzmon-Workshop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/education-1/|title=MUSIC EDUCATION|accessdate=3 January 2018|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2015|publisher=Gilad Atzmon}}</ref> A musical transcription of ten saxophone solos by Atzmon was released in 2010.<ref>Chris Gumbley, [http://www.gumblespublications.co.uk/saxophone-solos/ Gilad Uncovered: 10 Transcriptions], Gumbles Publications, 2010.</ref>\n\nAccording to reviewer [[Chris Searle]] in 2010, writing in the ''[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', \"No jazz musicians have done more to honour, publicise and spread solidarity with the struggle of the Palestinians than Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble.\u201d<ref>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 Review of the book ''Jazz Jews'' by Mike Gerber] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175013/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 |date=23 October 2017 }}, ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', February 2010.</ref>\n\n===Reviews and awards===\nAtzmon and his ensemble have received favorable reviews from the ''[[Financial Times]]'', ''[[The Scotsman]]'', ''[[Birmingham Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Bacon|first=Peter|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CULTURE%3A+Arts+reviews%3A+Activist+with+quotes+and+plenty+to+say%3B+Gilad...-a0127526728|title=Activist with quotes and plenty to say; Gilad Atzmon CBSO Centre|work=Birmingham Post| date=24 January 2005|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon web site].</ref> Reviews of his 2007 album ''Refuge'' included:\n:''[[Manchester Evening News]]'': \"The individuality of the music is extraordinary. No one is more willing to serve his music with raw political passion, and that curious [[Hazzan|cantor]]-like tone on clarinet is immediately arresting, like [[Artie Shaw]] writhing in his death throes.\"<ref>Alan Brownlee, [http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/world_music/s/1015/1015003_gilad_atzmon__the_orient_house_ensemble__refuge_enja.html Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble&nbsp;\u2013 Refuge (Enja)], [[Manchester Evening News]], 30 August 2007.</ref>\n:[[BBC]]: \"...the OHE is finding its voice in an increasingly subtle blend of East and West, that\u2019s brutal and beautiful.\"<ref>Kathryn Shackleton, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/5vp2/ Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble, Refuge], [[BBC]], 1 October 2007.</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, ''[[The Guardian]]'' jazz critic [[John Fordham (jazz critic)|John Fordham]] reviewed Atzmon's newest album ''In loving memory of America'' which was described by Atzmon as \"a memory of America I had cherished in my mind for many years\". It includes five standards and six originals \"inspired by the sumptuous harmonies and impassioned sax-playing of [[Charlie Parker|(Charlie) Parker]]'s late-40s recordings with classical strings\".<ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/27/gilad-atzmon-loving-memory-america \"Gilad Atzmon: In Loving Memory of America\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 February 2009.</ref> Music journalist John Lewis has praised much of Atzmon's work and described Atzmon as \"one of London's finest saxophonists\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon was the recipient of the [[HMV]] ''Top Dog Award'' at the [[Jazz of Birmingham|Birmingham International Jazz Festival]] in 1996\u201398.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> Gilad Atzmon's ''Exile'' was BBC jazz album of the year in 2003.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/3107607.stm Jazz winners span generations], BBC, 30 July 2003.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nAtzmon has defined himself variously as a \"[[secular Jew]]\",<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> a \"proud self-hating Jew\"  in the style of [[Otto Weininger]],<ref name=\"Panayides\" >Theo Panayides, [https://web.archive.org/web/20100223072804/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/living/wandering-jazz-player/20100221 'Wandering jazz player,'], [[Cyprus Mail]], 21 February 2010: \"My ethical duty is to say the things that I know and feel. I\u2019m an artist. Do you know.. this is something I learned from Otto Weininger, the Austrian philosopher. He was a clever boy, killed himself when he was 21. ..He was definitely a proud self-hating Jew! I\u2019m not a self-hating Jew: I\u2019m a proud self-hating Jew! It\u2019s a big difference\u2026 I celebrate my hatred towards everything I represent \u2013 or better to say [everything] I\u2019m associated with\".</ref> an \"ex-Jew\",<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/a-new-jewish-goal-by-gilad-atzmon.html A New Jewish Goal], at his personal web site.</ref> \"a Jew who hates Judaism\",<ref>{{cite news|last=\u05d7\u05dc\u05d9\u05dc\u05d9|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d8\u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df|url=http://article.yedioth.co.il/default.aspx?articleid=5448|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=9 November 2011|language=Hebrew|quote=\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05e9\u05dd \u05d0\u05ea \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9 \u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d6\u05db\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05ea \u05de\u05d2\u05d3\u05dc\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d7\u05df \u05db\u05dc \u05d0\u05e1\u05e4\u05e7\u05d8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05db\u05d9. (As a Jew who hates Judaism, I put myself under a magnifying glass and examine every Jewish aspect in me).}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halily|first=Yaniv|title=The protocols of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4147243,00.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=14 November 2011}}</ref> and \"a Hebrew-speaking Palestinian\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/>\n\nHe has said: \"I don't write about politics, I write about ethics. I write about Identity. I write a lot about the [[Jewish Question]]&nbsp;\u2013 because I was born in the Jew-land, and my whole process in maturing into an adult was involved with the realisation that my people are living on stolen land.\"<ref name=\"Panayides\"/> Atzmon has said that his experience in the military of \"my people destroying other people left a big scar\" and led to his decision that he was deluded about Zionism.  Atzmon has compared \"the Jewish Ideology\" to that of the [[Nazis]] and has described Israel's policy toward the Palestinians as [[genocide]].<ref name=\"gibson\"/> He has condemned \"Jewishness\" as \"very much a supremacist, racist tendency\", but has also stated that \"I don't have anything against Jews in particular and you won't find that in my writings\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> Regarding the one-state solution, Atzmon concedes that such a state probably would be controlled by [[Islamist]]s, but says, \"That's their business\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has said his statements have lost him performance contracts, especially in the United States.<ref>Karen Abi-Ezzi, \"Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon\u201d, Chapter 7 of Olivier Urbain, Editor, ''Music and conflict transformation: harmonies and dissonances in geopolitics'', I.B. Tauris, 2008  [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA101&dq=urbain+atzmon+contracts&hl=en&ei=2wpFTPf2C8P88Ab03uDKDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 101].</ref> \n\n===Periodicals===\nAtzmon has written for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref>Examples of Gilad Atzmon in [[CounterPunch]]:[https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/09/18/vengeance-barbarism-and-tarantino-s-inglourious-basterds/ Vengeance, Barbarism and Tarantino's Inglourious Basterds], 18 September 2009; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/08/28/the-most-common-mistakes-of-israelis/ Collective Self-Deception: The Most Common Mistakes of Israelis], 28 August 2003; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/10/thinking-outside-of-the-secular-box/ The Left and Islam: Thinking Outside of the Secular Box], 10\u201312 July 2009.</ref> ''Uruknet'',<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://uruknet.info/?p=m31096&s1=h1 Purim Special, From Esther to AIPAC], Uruknet, 3 March 2007.</ref> and the ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',<ref>Example of Gilad Atzmon in ''The Palestine Telegraph'': [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/jewish-ideology-and-world-peace-by-gilad-atzmon.html 'Israeli Ideology and World Peace,'] 7 June 2010.</ref>. In 2009, he wrote for and edited the website, Palestine Think Tank.<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Novels===\nAtzmon's ''[[A Guide to the Perplexed]]'', published in 2001, is set in a 2052 in which Israel has been replaced by a Palestinian state. Jeffrey St. Clair in ''CounterPunch'' describes it as \"vividly written satire, infused with a ribald sense of humor and an unsparing critique of the incendiary political cauldron of the Mideast.\" It largely reviews memoirs of the alienated Israeli Gunther Wunker's rise to fame as a \"peepologist\", or voyeur. The perplexed are defined as \"the unthinking Chosen\" who \"cling to clods of earth that don't belong to them.\" The novel excoriates what it describes as the commercialization of the Holocaust and \"argues that the Holocaust is invoked as a kind of reflexive propaganda designed to shield the Zionist state from responsibility for any transgression against Palestinians.\"<ref name=\"St. Clair\">[[Jeffrey St. Clair]],[https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/07/17/gilad-atzmon-s-a-guide-to-the-perplexed/ 'Gilad Atzmon's \"A Guide to the Perplexed\",'] [[CounterPunch]] 17 July 2003</ref>\n\nMatthew J. Reisz, a reviewer for ''[[The Independent]]'', wrote that \"As a viciously black satire on Israeli life\" the book \"is grandiose, childish and nasty, but with just enough connection with reality to give it a certain unsettling power\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Reisz|first=Matthew J.|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/a-guide-to-the-perplexed-by-gilad-atzmon-trans-philip-simpson-609999.html|title=A Guide to the Perplexed, by Gilad Atzmon, trans. Philip Simpson|work=The Independent|date=7 December 2002|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} Darren King in ''[[The Observer]]'' noted of this \"provocative debut novel\" that it is \"odd to mix knob gags with highly serious assertions\", but thought it works because \"Atzmon writes with so much style and his gags are so hilarious\".<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Darren|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/featuresreviews.guardianreview16|title=Mr. Peepology|work=The Observer|date=25 January 2003|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', \"Atzmon clearly wants to provoke, but his approach is so familiar that few readers will take the bait.\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-85242-826-6 \"A Guide to the Perplexed\"], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', 31 March 2003.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's second novel, ''My One and Only Love'', was published in 2005 and features as a protagonist a trumpeter who chooses to play only one note (extremely well), as well as a spy who uncovers Nazi war criminals and locks them inside double bass cases which then tour permanently in the protagonist's orchestra's luggage.<ref>Sholto Byrnes. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/talking-jazz-529796.html \"Talking Jazz\"], ''The Independent'', 25 March 2005</ref> The book is also a comedic take on \"Zionist espionage and intrigue\" which explores \"the personal conflict between being true to one\u2019s heart and being loyal to The Jews\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2004/10/01/gilad_event_feature.shtml \"Gilad Atzmon's Orient House Ensemble \u2013 The Junction\"], BBC Cambridgeshire, 3 June 2005.</ref>\n\n===Nonfiction===\nIn 2011, [[Zero Books]] published Atzmon's book, ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics'', stating that it \"examines Jewish identity politics and Jewish contemporary ideology using both popular culture and scholarly texts.\"<ref name = WanderingBook>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=rTbtBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&lpg=PT7 ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics''], Zero Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84694-875-6}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jean Bricmont]], in his preface for the French edition, ''La Parabole d\u2019Esther'', Atzmon starts by giving three definitions of 'Jewish': (a) it may refer to adherents of Judaism, and he has no quarrel with them; (b) secondly, it may refer to ethnic Jews, and, likewise, he sees no problem in that; (c) thirdly, it can refer to a third category, those who, without being particularly religious, place great emphasis on their Jewish \"identity\" as something more important than their basic membership of the human race.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" >[[Jean Bricmont]], [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/counterpunch-print-edition-in-defense-of-gilad-atzmon-by-jea.html  'In Defense of Gilad Atzmon By Jean Bricmont,'] Counterpunch April 2012 print edition, cited on Atzmon's blog.</ref> Bricmont then adds that it is very easy to mount a case to 'prove' Atzmon is an antisemite by consistently construing his criticisms of (c) as though they were aimed as (a) or (b) or both.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" /> \n\n[[Marc H. Ellis]],  professor of Jewish studies at [[Baylor University]], likens Atzmon's rhetorical extremism and harsh censure of Jews to the [[Prophet|prophetic voices]] of the [[Old Testament]], arguing that, for Atzmon, [[Diaspora|diasporic]] Jews are asked to construct their identity on the basis of the [[State of Israel]] and the [[Holocaust]], an identity he regards as without foundation. He adds that Atzmon considers charges that he is antisemitic as 'last ditch attempts' to validate that identity. In Ellis's view, there may be, in the perceived anxiety in these repeated attacks, a reflection of the same anxiety Atzmon himself arguably embodies.<ref name=\"Ellis\" >[[Marc H. Ellis]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=doN-AwAAQBAJ&dq=Marc+Ellis%2BGilad+Atzmon&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y  ''Future of the Prophetic: Israel's Ancient Wisdom Re-presented,''] [[Fortress Press]], 2014 pp.331\u2013332.</ref><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/the-new-jewish-prophet.html  'The New Jewish Prophet,'] 24 June 2014.</ref> {{efn|Ellis also notes that Atzmon considers the bible 'bogus'.<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> Atzmon himself cites evidence 600 passages in the OT are violent, and argues that this 'lethal spirit of the scriptures has infused the essence of modern Jewish political discourse,' underwriting in his view even the secular mindset of military commanders conducting war in Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.<ref>G. Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA122 ''The Wandering Who,''] 2011 p.122.</ref>}}\n\nRichard Falk commented \"Atzmon has written an absorbing and moving account of his journey from hard-core Israeli nationalist to a de-Zionized patriot of humanity\".<ref>Stephen M. Walt,[http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], 26 September 2011 (posted on Walt.Foreignpolicy.com)</ref> \n\nMearsheimer wrote \"There is no question that the book is provocative, both in terms of its central argument and the overly hot language that Atzmon sometimes uses. But it is also filled with interesting insights that make the reader think long and hard about an important subject.\"\nadding, \"to be perfectly clear, he has no animus toward Judaism as a religion or with individuals who are Jewish by birth. Rather, his target is the tribalism that he believes is common to most Jews, and I might add, to most other peoples as well.\"<ref>Stephen Walt, [http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref> \n\nTen authors published by Zero Books, including [[Laurie Penny]] and [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]], criticised Zero Books for publishing it, arguing that \"The thrust of Atzmon's work is to normalise and legitimise anti-Semitism.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leninology.blogspot.com/2011/09/zero-authors-statement-on-gilad-atzmon.html|title=Zero Authors Statement on Gilad Atzmon|publisher=Lenin's Tomb|date=26 September 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAtzmon characterised some of the criticism as an \"orchestrated attack\" and a \"typical [[Hasbara]] smear & intimidation campaign\u201d<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/goldberg-vs-mearsheimer-by-gilad-atzmon.html Goldberg vs. Mearsheimer], Gilad Atzmon website, 25 September 2011.</ref> and wrote that his book \"is a study of Jewish identity politics and Jewish culture, it is not concerned with Jewish ethnicity or racial origins.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-supremacists-on-the-wandering-who.html \"Supremacists on 'The Wandering Who'\"], Gilad.co.uk, 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's 2015 book, ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon'', was summarised by Eugene Schulman in ''CounterPunch'' as \"designed to alphabetically define certain aspects of Zionism and Zionist personalities in one-liner jabs.\" and called it as a book which would \"knock a hole in all your prejudices.\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/05/22/on-gilad-atzmons-the-definitive-israeli-lexicon/|title=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/05/22/on-gilad-atzmons-the-definitive-israeli-lexicon/|last=Schulman|first=Eugene|date=22 May 2015|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=CounterPunch}}</ref>\n\nAtzmon's fifth book, ''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', published in 2017, was described by [[James Petras]] as \"a brilliant and substantive critique of identity politics and Jewish political ideology and culture\" and as \"an essential read for understanding and confronting authoritarianism of all stripes and colors.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gilad.online/being-in-time|title=Endorsements|last=Petras|first=James|accessdate=1 May 2020|work=Gilad}}</ref> [[Keith Kahn-Harris]], in an opinion piece, argued that its critique of identity politics and ascription of it to Jewishness was inherently antisemitic.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kahn-Harris|first=Keith|url=https://forward.com/opinion/389696/cloaked-in-pretensions-gilad-atzmons-anti-semitism-soldiers-on/|title=Cloaked In Pretensions, Gilad Atzmon\u2019s Anti-Semitism Soldiers On|work=Forward|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of antisemitism==\nSeveral of Atzmon's statements regarding Jews and Judaism have led to allegations of antisemitism. \n\n===Criticism===\nIn a 2005 opinion piece, [[David Aaronovitch]] criticized Atzmon for his essay \"On Anti-Semitism\" and for making the case for free speech on the Holocaust.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\">{{cite news|last=Aaronovitch|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-did-the-far-left-manage-to-slip-into-bed-with-the-jew-hating-right-766cbwpdqfd|title=How did the far Left manage to slip into bed with the Jew-hating Right?|work=The Times|location=London|date=28 June 2005|accessdate=24 February 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 opinion piece, [[David Hirsh]] criticised what he called Atzmon's \"openly anti-Jewish rhetoric\", including [[Jewish deicide]].<ref>Hirsh, David. [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/nov/30/anewmenacingcurrentisappe Openly embracing prejudice], ''The Guardian'', 30 November 2006. Hirsh also refers to the statement in [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/apr/03/nobodyhaseverclaimedthatc \"What charge?\"], \"The Guardian\", 3 April 2006.</ref> In response to a question about this Atzmon replied, in ''CounterPunch'', \"I find it astonishing that people today happen to be offended by such accusations (i.e. about an event almost 2000 years ago.)\"<ref>[https://www.counterpunch.org/2007/02/15/quot-do-i-look-like-the-pope-quot/ \"Are You a Christian?\" \"Do I Look Like the Pope?\"&nbsp;\u2013 An Exchange Between Lenni Brenner & Gilad Atzmon], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 15 February 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, David Landy, an Irish academic and former chair of the Ireland Palestine Solidarity Campaign, wrote that Atzmon's words, \"if not actually anti-Semitic, certainly border on it\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Landy|first=David|title=Jewish Identity and Palestinian Rights: Disapora Jewish Opposition to Israel|year=2011|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-84813-926-8|page=167}}</ref> \n\nA group of mainly US-based Palestinian activists, including [[Ali Abunimah]], [[Naseer Aruri]], [[Omar Barghouti]], [[Nadia Hijab]] and [[Joseph Massad]], called in March 2012 for \"the disavowal of Atzmon by fellow Palestinian organizers, as well as Palestine solidarity activists, and allies of the Palestinian people\" and affirming that \"we regard any attempt to link and adopt antisemitic or racist language, even if it is within a self-described anti-imperialist and anti-Zionist politics, as reaffirming and legitimizing Zionism.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Granting No Quarter: A Call for the Disavowal of the Racism and Antisemitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://uspcn.org/2012/03/13/granting-no-quarter-a-call-for-the-disavowal-of-the-racism-and-antisemitism-of-gilad-atzmon|publisher=US Palestinian Community Network|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[Anti-Defamation League]] described Atzmon as \"an outspoken promoter of classic anti-Semitic conspiracy theories and a fierce\ncritic of the State of Israel (who) has engaged in Holocaust diminution and has defended the right of\nHolocaust deniers to challenge historical narratives and offer revisionist theories about the Holocaust.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/profiles/gilad-atzmon|title=Gilad Atzmon|publisher=ADL|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Comments===\nAt a talk by Richard Falk at [[London School of Economics|LSE]] in March 2017, which was being disrupted by pro-Israel activists, Atzmon was alleged to have commented that Jews had been \"expelled from Germany for misbehaving\" and also to have suggested that people should read Holocaust denier [[David Irving]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-students-told-dont-study-at-lse-by-board-president/|title=Jewish students told 'don\u2019t study at LSE' by Board president|work=Jewish News Online|date=23 March 2017|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Responses===\nAtzmon refers to charges of antisemitism as being a \"common Zionist silencing apparatus.\"<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], Interview with Gilad Atzmon in ''London Tour Dates'' magazine, 5 October 2006</ref> He denies that he is an antisemite and states that, \"Because 'Anti-Semite' is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have.\"<ref name=1001Lies>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/1001-lies-about-gilad-atzmon.html 1001 Lies About Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon com. 18 June 2011 \"I am an anti Zionist and oppose the Zionist mindset. I look at questions of Jewish identity and I do question the ties between a Jewish world view and Zionism. I refute totally that I am anti-Semite. In fact I also believe that the current concept of an Anti-Semitism is meaningless. Once the Zionists had managed to establish their Jewish state, any form of anti Jewish sentiments should be comprehended either as a private case of xenophobia or as a political retaliation to Israeli/Zionist atrocities. In other words, the title Anti-Semite became an \u2018empty signifier, i.e. a signifier with a vague, highly variable, unspecifiable or non-existent signified. It is an empty verbal utterance that exists merely to serve a political cause (very much like Blair\u2019s WMD and Bush\u2019s Axis of Evil). Because Anti-Semite is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have\".</ref> In 2009, Atzmon said \"I've got nothing against the Semite people, I don't have anything against people&nbsp;\u2014 I'm anti-Jewish, not anti-Jews.\"<ref name=\"gibson\">Gibson, Martin. \"No choice but to speak out&nbsp;\u2014 Israeli musician 'a proud self-hating Jew'\", ''The Gisborne Herald'', 23 January 2009.</ref> He added that \"Stupidly we interpreted the Nazi defeat as a vindication of the Jewish ideology and the Jewish people\"; however, \"in fact Jewish ideology and Nazi ideology were very similar.\"<ref name=\"gibson\"/> \n\nAtzmon has stated \" I do not deny the Holocaust or the Nazi Judeocide. But I just insist that both the Holocaust and World War II should be treated as historical events rather than as religious myth....The most crucial question here is why we are not allowed to treat that very historical chapter applying academic methods. The answer is very simple. The Holocaust is now regarded by most Jews and Anglo-Americans as the new Western religion...But then, even if we accept the Holocaust as the new Anglo-American liberal-democratic religion, we must allow people to be atheists.\"<ref name=\"Beauty\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|title=Beauty as a political weapon; Three in one: jazzman, writer and activist&nbsp;\u2013 A conversation with Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072556/http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|archivedate=3 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Talens\" >[[:es:Manuel Talens|Manuel Talens]],  [http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=24333 'La belleza como arma pol\u00edtica,'] [[Rebelion.org]] 19 December 2005,</ref> \n\n[[Oren Ben-Dor]] wrote in ''CounterPunch'' in 2008 \"I am firmly convinced that these vulgar attempts at silencing of Gilad and other courageous voices offends against supremely thoughtful, compassionate and egalitarian intellectual endeavours.\"<ref>[[Oren Ben-Dor]], [https://www.counterpunch.org/2008/03/15/the-silencing-of-gilad-atzmon/ 'The Silencing of Gilad Atzmon'], [[CounterPunch]], 15 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[Norton Mezvinsky]] wrote that \"Gilad Atzmon is a critical and committed secular humanist with firm views, who delights in being provocative.\"<ref>[[Norton Mezvinsky]], [http://wrmea.org/archives/507-washington-report-archives-2011-2015/may-2012/11161-gilad-atzmon-and-the-wandering-who.html Gilad Atzmon and The Wandering Who?], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.wrmea.org/action-alert-archives/11194-engaging-gilad-atzmon.html 'Engaging Gilad Atzmon], video of Norton Mezvinsky interview with Gilad Atzmon,' [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref>\n\n==Libel suit==\nIn July 2018, Atzmon issued an apology to Gideon Falter, the chairman of the [[Campaign Against Antisemitism]] after being sued for libel. Atzmon had alleged that Falter had personally profited from fabricating antisemitic incidents. Atzmon was also liable for legal costs and damages.<ref name=\"Libel\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Ben |title=Gilad Atzmon is forced to apologise to CAA's Gideon Falter over libel |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/gideon-falter-gilad-atzmon-1.466405 |accessdate=3 July 2018 |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CAA\">{{cite web |title=Antisemitic author and saxophonist Gilad Atzmon capitulates, making humiliating apology and paying substantial damages and costs after just two hours in court against CAA |url=https://antisemitism.uk/antisemitic-author-and-saxophonist-gilad-atzmon-capitulates-making-humiliating-apology-and-paying-substantial-damages-and-costs-after-just-two-hours-in-court-against-caa/ |website=antisemitism.uk |publisher=Campaign Against Antisemitism |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The Spirit of Trane'' (Fanfare Jazz, 2017)\n*''World Peace Trio'' (Enja, 2017)\n*''Songs of the Metropolis'' (World Village, 2013)\n*''The Tide Has Changed'' (World Village, 2010)\n*''In Loving Memory of America'' (Enja, 2009)\n*''Refuge'' (Enja, 2007)\n*''Artie Fishel and the Promised Band'' (WMD, 2006)\n*''MusiK'' (Enja, 2004)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/oct/08/jazz.shopping1</ref>\n*''Exile'' (Enja, 2004)\n*''Nostalgico'' (Enja, 2001)\n*''Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble'' (Enja, 2000)\n*''Juizz Muzic'' (FruitBeard, 1999)\n*''Take It or Leave It'' (Face Jazz, 1997)\n*''Spiel: Both Sides'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel Acid Jazz Band'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel'' (In Acoustic & H.M. Acoustica, 1993)\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book |title=[[A Guide to the Perplexed]] |translator= Philip Simpson |location=London|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]] |year=2002 |isbn=1-85242-826-0}}\n*''My one and only love''. London: Saqi Books, 2005. {{ISBN|0-86356-507-7}} (pbk.). {{ISBN|978-0-86356-507-6}} (pbk.)\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C| title=The Wandering Who?: A Study of Jewish Identity Politics |publisher=[[John Hunt Publishing|Zero Books]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-84694-875-6}}\n* ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon''. London, Fanfare Press, 2015.{{ISBN|978-0993183706}} (pbk.). \n*''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', Newbold on Stour, Warwickshire: Skyscraper Publications, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1911072201}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brian Lenzo, [http://www.palestinechronicle.com/old/view_article_details.php?id=16132 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed: Each Village is a Reminder], originally published by Socialist Worker Online, 13 July 2010 (reprinted by the Palestine Chronicle).{{Deadlink|date=April 2020}}\n*[http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/eveningnews24/norwich-whats-on-guide/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=GoingOutMusic&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=WhatsOn&itemid=NOED26%20Nov%202009%2016%3A03%3A06%3A953 Interview: Gilad Atzmon] by Rob Garratt, Evening News 24, 11 November 2009.{{Deadlink|date=April 2020}}\n*[https://archive.org/details/GiladAtzmonOnArabvoices.netJune2009 Gilad Atzmon interview on ArabVoices.net], [[KPFT]], June 2009 during visit to Houston, Texas.\n*Ivan Hewett, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3667959/Gilad-Altzmon-High-flown-ecstasies-from-an-angry-man.html Gilad Altzmon: High-flown ecstasies from an angry man], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 17 September 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133806/http://middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21321 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed by Mary Rizzo], Middle East Online, July 2007.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon website]\n\n{{The Blockheads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atzmon, Gilad}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:Anti-Judaism]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism]]\n[[Category:Bebop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:The Blockheads members]]\n[[Category:British jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:British male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Writers on Zionism]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "